<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1324,284,1870]" box="[264,400,284,310]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Coloration: Body mostly yellowish brown; head, antennae, rostrum, fore legs, posterior lateral angles of fourth to sixth connexival segments reddish brown to brownish red (
<figureCitation box="[323,410,404,430]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,367,1861,1885]" captionTargetBox="[362,1218,681,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-67@3.[354,1227,675,1825]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., ♂. Habitus. Scale bar = 3.33 mm" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[431,448,404,430]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–7" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1735,1759]" captionTargetBox="[378,1223,321,1698]" captionTargetId="figure-97@5.[360,1223,313,1702]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2–7. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., 2, 4–7, ♂, 3, ♀. 2, Head and pronotum, antennae removed; 3, apical portion of abdomen; 4, apical portion of abdomen; 5, abdomen; 6, apex of abdomen; 7, pygophore. 2, 5, 7, lateral view; 6, caudal view; 3, 4, ventral view. Scale bar of 2, 3, 4 = 1.33 mm; of 5 = 2.00 mm; of 6 = 1.00 mm; of 7 = 0.67 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">5</figureCitation>
); eyes brownish red with dark irregular markings, ocelli light yellow; abdomen beneath, four long spines on posterior pronotal lobe brownish black to black (
<figureCitation box="[273,354,484,510]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,367,1861,1885]" captionTargetBox="[362,1218,681,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-67@3.[354,1227,675,1825]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., ♂. Habitus. Scale bar = 3.33 mm" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[369,414,484,510]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–7" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1735,1759]" captionTargetBox="[378,1223,321,1698]" captionTargetId="figure-97@5.[360,1223,313,1702]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2–7. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., 2, 4–7, ♂, 3, ♀. 2, Head and pronotum, antennae removed; 3, apical portion of abdomen; 4, apical portion of abdomen; 5, abdomen; 6, apex of abdomen; 7, pygophore. 2, 5, 7, lateral view; 6, caudal view; 3, 4, ventral view. Scale bar of 2, 3, 4 = 1.33 mm; of 5 = 2.00 mm; of 6 = 1.00 mm; of 7 = 0.67 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">2, 5</figureCitation>
); coxa, pronotum (except long spines on posterior pronotal lobe), ventral and lateral sides of thorax, markings of inner portion of third to seventh connexival segments (
<figureCitation box="[273,353,564,590]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–7" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1735,1759]" captionTargetBox="[378,1223,321,1698]" captionTargetId="figure-97@5.[360,1223,313,1702]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2–7. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., 2, 4–7, ♂, 3, ♀. 2, Head and pronotum, antennae removed; 3, apical portion of abdomen; 4, apical portion of abdomen; 5, abdomen; 6, apex of abdomen; 7, pygophore. 2, 5, 7, lateral view; 6, caudal view; 3, 4, ventral view. Scale bar of 2, 3, 4 = 1.33 mm; of 5 = 2.00 mm; of 6 = 1.00 mm; of 7 = 0.67 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) light brown to brown; posterior margin of pronotum, scutellum, corium, connexivum (except posterior angles of fourth to sixth connexival segments) yellowish; corium with some small wax­like spots; most of mid and hind legs, yellowish brown to reddish brown; membrane and claw yellowish, semitransparent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Structure: Body large and elongate. Body clothed with white, short, bent pubescence and subvertical setae; first and second antennal segments with scattered oblique short setae, third and fourth segments with dense oblique short setae; first rostral segment with dense oblique short setae, second and third segments with sparse setae; legs clothed with oblique short setae and subvertical long setae, ventral surface of fore leg with abundant short erect setae; head, pronotum, scutellum, corium, lateral and ventral surface of thorax, abdomen clothed with pubescence and subvertical long setae. Head cylindrical; processes behind base of antennae short (
<figureCitation box="[634,717,1004,1030]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,367,1861,1885]" captionTargetBox="[362,1218,681,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-67@3.[354,1227,675,1825]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., ♂. Habitus. Scale bar = 3.33 mm" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[732,749,1004,1030]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–7" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1735,1759]" captionTargetBox="[378,1223,321,1698]" captionTargetId="figure-97@5.[360,1223,313,1702]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2–7. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., 2, 4–7, ♂, 3, ♀. 2, Head and pronotum, antennae removed; 3, apical portion of abdomen; 4, apical portion of abdomen; 5, abdomen; 6, apex of abdomen; 7, pygophore. 2, 5, 7, lateral view; 6, caudal view; 3, 4, ventral view. Scale bar of 2, 3, 4 = 1.33 mm; of 5 = 2.00 mm; of 6 = 1.00 mm; of 7 = 0.67 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">2</figureCitation>
); first antennal segment longest and subequal to or slightly longer than third segment, fourth segment shortest and slightly shorter than second segment; eyes protruding laterally; ocelli widely separated; first rostral segment slightly longer than second segment, third segment shortest (
<figureCitation box="[977,1049,1124,1150]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–7" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1735,1759]" captionTargetBox="[378,1223,321,1698]" captionTargetId="figure-97@5.[360,1223,313,1702]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2–7. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., 2, 4–7, ♂, 3, ♀. 2, Head and pronotum, antennae removed; 3, apical portion of abdomen; 4, apical portion of abdomen; 5, abdomen; 6, apex of abdomen; 7, pygophore. 2, 5, 7, lateral view; 6, caudal view; 3, 4, ventral view. Scale bar of 2, 3, 4 = 1.33 mm; of 5 = 2.00 mm; of 6 = 1.00 mm; of 7 = 0.67 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Pronotum developed, nearly as long as wide; collar processes spine­shaped produced anteriorly, round at apex; middle longitudinal sulcus of anterior lobe deep at base; posterior pronotal lobe nearly twice as long as anterior lobe; anterior margin concave, posterior margin nearly straight; two large spines at middle of posterior part of posterior lobe very strong, erect and acute (
<figureCitation box="[273,361,1324,1350]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,367,1861,1885]" captionTargetBox="[362,1218,681,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-67@3.[354,1227,675,1825]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., ♂. Habitus. Scale bar = 3.33 mm" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[383,400,1324,1350]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–7" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1735,1759]" captionTargetBox="[378,1223,321,1698]" captionTargetId="figure-97@5.[360,1223,313,1702]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2–7. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., 2, 4–7, ♂, 3, ♀. 2, Head and pronotum, antennae removed; 3, apical portion of abdomen; 4, apical portion of abdomen; 5, abdomen; 6, apex of abdomen; 7, pygophore. 2, 5, 7, lateral view; 6, caudal view; 3, 4, ventral view. Scale bar of 2, 3, 4 = 1.33 mm; of 5 = 2.00 mm; of 6 = 1.00 mm; of 7 = 0.67 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">2</figureCitation>
); lateral pronotal angles spine­shaped produced laterally; posterior angles round, slightly protruding; scutellum distinctly wider than long, with “Y”­shaped carina, apex round; profemur thickest; third tarsomere slightly longer than first and second tarsomeres combined. Abdominal connexivum expanded laterally, posterior angles of fourth to sixth segments protruded (
<figureCitation box="[691,772,1484,1510]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,367,1861,1885]" captionTargetBox="[362,1218,681,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-67@3.[354,1227,675,1825]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., ♂. Habitus. Scale bar = 3.33 mm" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[789,806,1484,1510]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–7" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1735,1759]" captionTargetBox="[378,1223,321,1698]" captionTargetId="figure-97@5.[360,1223,313,1702]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2–7. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., 2, 4–7, ♂, 3, ♀. 2, Head and pronotum, antennae removed; 3, apical portion of abdomen; 4, apical portion of abdomen; 5, abdomen; 6, apex of abdomen; 7, pygophore. 2, 5, 7, lateral view; 6, caudal view; 3, 4, ventral view. Scale bar of 2, 3, 4 = 1.33 mm; of 5 = 2.00 mm; of 6 = 1.00 mm; of 7 = 0.67 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">5</figureCitation>
). Discal cell of hemelytra longer than wide and very small; base of inner cell wider than that of outer cell (
<figureCitation box="[1021,1091,1524,1550]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,367,1861,1885]" captionTargetBox="[362,1218,681,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-67@3.[354,1227,675,1825]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., ♂. Habitus. Scale bar = 3.33 mm" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Abdominal tip of female as shown in 
<figureCitation box="[500,572,1564,1590]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–7" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1735,1759]" captionTargetBox="[378,1223,321,1698]" captionTargetId="figure-97@5.[360,1223,313,1702]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2–7. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., 2, 4–7, ♂, 3, ♀. 2, Head and pronotum, antennae removed; 3, apical portion of abdomen; 4, apical portion of abdomen; 5, abdomen; 6, apex of abdomen; 7, pygophore. 2, 5, 7, lateral view; 6, caudal view; 3, 4, ventral view. Scale bar of 2, 3, 4 = 1.33 mm; of 5 = 2.00 mm; of 6 = 1.00 mm; of 7 = 0.67 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
. Pygophore oblong, median pygophore process round and wide (
<figureCitation box="[273,387,1604,1630]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–7" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1735,1759]" captionTargetBox="[378,1223,321,1698]" captionTargetId="figure-97@5.[360,1223,313,1702]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2–7. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., 2, 4–7, ♂, 3, ♀. 2, Head and pronotum, antennae removed; 3, apical portion of abdomen; 4, apical portion of abdomen; 5, abdomen; 6, apex of abdomen; 7, pygophore. 2, 5, 7, lateral view; 6, caudal view; 3, 4, ventral view. Scale bar of 2, 3, 4 = 1.33 mm; of 5 = 2.00 mm; of 6 = 1.00 mm; of 7 = 0.67 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs. 6, 7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[401,416,1604,1630]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[348,1265,346,1654]" captionTargetId="figure-71@6.[297,1290,295,1703]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., ♂. 8, pygophore; 9, 10, paramere; pygophore; 11, 12, phallus; 13, phallosoma; 14, struts. 8, 13, ventral view; 12, dorsal view; 11, lateral view. Scale bar of 8 = 1.00 mm; of 9–13 = 0.75 mm; of 14 = 0.375 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">8</figureCitation>
); paramere clavate and bent, sharp at apex, and subapical portion with long setae (
<figureCitation box="[340,470,1644,1670]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[348,1265,346,1654]" captionTargetId="figure-71@6.[297,1290,295,1703]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., ♂. 8, pygophore; 9, 10, paramere; pygophore; 11, 12, phallus; 13, phallosoma; 14, struts. 8, 13, ventral view; 12, dorsal view; 11, lateral view. Scale bar of 8 = 1.00 mm; of 9–13 = 0.75 mm; of 14 = 0.375 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs. 9, 10</figureCitation>
); basal plate of phallus thin and curved, basal plate bridge thin, slightly arched in middle; pedicel short and wide; phallosoma ovate in dorsal and ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[273,424,1724,1750]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[348,1265,346,1654]" captionTargetId="figure-71@6.[297,1290,295,1703]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., ♂. 8, pygophore; 9, 10, paramere; pygophore; 11, 12, phallus; 13, phallosoma; 14, struts. 8, 13, ventral view; 12, dorsal view; 11, lateral view. Scale bar of 8 = 1.00 mm; of 9–13 = 0.75 mm; of 14 = 0.375 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs. 12, 13</figureCitation>
), and bent upwards at apex in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[978,1069,1724,1750]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[348,1265,346,1654]" captionTargetId="figure-71@6.[297,1290,295,1703]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., ♂. 8, pygophore; 9, 10, paramere; pygophore; 11, 12, phallus; 13, phallosoma; 14, struts. 8, 13, ventral view; 12, dorsal view; 11, lateral view. Scale bar of 8 = 1.00 mm; of 9–13 = 0.75 mm; of 14 = 0.375 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
); dorsal phallothecal sclerite warped upward at apical part, middle of distal margin feebly concave (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[348,1265,346,1654]" captionTargetId="figure-71@6.[297,1290,295,1703]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Epidaus bachmaensis Truong, Zhao &amp; Cai, sp. nov., ♂. 8, pygophore; 9, 10, paramere; pygophore; 11, 12, phallus; 13, phallosoma; 14, struts. 8, 13, ventral view; 12, dorsal view; 11, lateral view. Scale bar of 8 = 1.00 mm; of 9–13 = 0.75 mm; of 14 = 0.375 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs. 11, 12</figureCitation>
